posts.name: Jaci
posts.cooked: Grapple Robotics has partnered with The Thrifty Bot to launch several new products at CHAMP. Grapple will stock parts in their Australian stores, while The Thrifty Bot will supply items from their US stores, ensuring faster shipping. Both companies will co-develop future products and share a CAN specification for seamless integration. Launches include the LaserCAN with an ESD-safe case, MitoCANdria with advanced voltage support and regulated 5V rail, and FlexiCAN offering a compact design with multiple connectivity options. Visit [www.chiefdelphi.com](http://www.chiefdelphi.com) or contact Jaci for more details. Attend the event at Worlds 2024 to experience these innovations firsthand. Note that Jaci will not be present due to personal commitments, but the event remains a must-attend for all FRC enthusiasts!

posts.name: Will Toth
posts.cooked: I’ve been wanting a CAN Controller Area Network connected regulator for a while, and it looks great! For the MitoCANdria you mentioned, the transient input range is 4.5-14V, but with the latest brushless motors, voltage transients can exceed 16V or even higher. Without a battery, teams are experiencing issues with fried Limelights due to these transients. Is 14V the final limit, or should we consider expanding the input voltage range?

posts.name: Max Morehead
posts.cooked:
Here is the cleaned-up version of the provided text, adhering strictly to your instructions:

Grapple and Thrifty electronics products are cross-compatible under the CAN specification, which allows them to function seamlessly within GrappleHook. Additionally, both FRC (FIRST Robotics Competition) and CAN standards are being considered for future developments. One could imagine this technology eventually integrating into FRC-eligible motor controllers. Furthermore, questions arise regarding the availability of open-source firmware for FlexiCAN and MitoCANdria.

posts.name: Jaci
posts.cooked: The MitoCANdria can manage higher transients above 14V, featuring an ESD diode to divert excess voltage beyond 14-15V, ensuring the boost regulator operates efficiently.

posts.name: Jaci
posts.cooked: Is it weird that in a post full of amazing announcements, this is the most exciting? Seems like a big step towards an open and cross-compatible FIRST Robotics Competition Controller Area Network standard. We are working on a proposal regarding an open Controller Area Network standard designed specifically for FIRST Robotics Competition, hoping to share more soon. Will the firmware for FlexiCAN and MitoCANdria be open source? Since the MitoCANdria and FlexiCAN are joint products between Grapple and Thrifty, this is still something we’re figuring out. At the very least, we will definitely be sharing our Controller Area Network infrastructure in the open source domain, including messaging formats, fragmentation/defragmentation, etc. For the FlexiCAN, there will be a WASM stack that will be open-sourced to allow teams to build whatever code they like on top of the FlexiCAN’s base.

posts.name: Jordan McMichael
posts.cooked: When do you think these products will become available for purchase? I’m eager to get my hands on a FlexiCAN. Can end users access and manage data traffic?

posts.name: Jaci
posts.cooked: We'll be opening up orders for the LaserCAN again once we get the kitting fully sorted out (case and all), so hopefully within the next month or two I may make another revision of the LaserCAN at some point which supports FD, but it's not currently on the cards. In theory, the CAN FD devices should be compatible with a CANivore when running at 8Mbps, but CTRE doesn't expose their interface for other vendors. The FlexiCAN will also behave like a CAN FD ↔ USB bridge like the CANivore, but will be open to all vendors, but it will ultimately be up to their API whether they support it or not.

posts.name: Jaci
posts.cooked: I'm afraid not; the ADJ rail is pure boost, meaning the minimum voltage must match the robot battery voltage. Most FRC electronics, such as sensors, radio, and Limelight support, operate at least 15V, allowing a regulated power rail for these components. Additionally, 19V is often used for mini PCs and more demanding devices, while 24V remains the upper limit for FRC applications according to current rules and is widely used industrially.

posts.name: Jaci
posts.cooked:
We’re currently targeting some time in June – we’ve allocated time for another 1-2 prototyping runs and beta testing. Following that, assuming they pass their tests successfully, they’ll become available for purchase. Our current lead time for prototypes to be manufactured is approximately 2 weeks, and we plan to give teams time to test them extensively before release.  

Primitive CAN read/writes, including arbitrary-ID frames and Manufacturer ID=8 dedicated frames, will be accessible to users. Reads will operate via polling due to limitations in WASM, but they will be buffered and exposed similar to the embedded-hal ecosystem (e.g., selecting a Message ID and Message Mask to filter bus activity).

posts.name: Matt
posts.cooked: Excited to learn more about the MitoCANdria’s programmable output voltage feature, which is perfect for power-hungry SBCs, and appreciate the opportunity to explore its capabilities within the FIRST Robotics Competition-specific power regulator domain. Can you provide more details on how the CAN configurable voltage output works? I’m particularly interested in understanding how this might integrate into our systems and if there are any concerns regarding potential pitfalls or code-driven failure modes that we should be aware of.

posts.name: Technologyman00
posts.cooked: Here’s my hope at least. No programmed output means either no output or very low voltage, which shouldn’t harm anything. Persistent storage would be nice; setting it once could prevent future issues.

posts.name: Jaci
posts.cooked: This is indeed how it functions - all switchable output channels are locked off until either the voltage is set from the RoboRIO and the channel is explicitly turned on or a configuration is loaded at startup containing this requirement. All switchable outputs are electrically off by default, ensuring that if the microcontroller fails the channels will remain off. Configurations are persistently stored so the MitoCANdria retains its previous state upon startup. The adjustable channel includes additional safeguards, such as enabling only when the rail is within an acceptable voltage range and preventing operation during overvoltage conditions through overvoltage lockout protection.
